  "text": "C4 plants are named for the four-carbon organic acids produced in the first product of carbon fixation. C4 plants have an improved photosynthetic efficiency with minimized water loss in hot and dry environments. Generally, these kind of species are native to the tropics and warmer climates with high light intensity exhibiting a higher photosynthetic and growth rate due to gains in the water, carbon and nitrogen efficiency uses [24] . Maize (Zea mays), sugar cane (Saccharum officinarum) and sorghum (Sorghum bicolor) are among the most productive crops with C4 photosynthesis pathway [CITATION_1] . Although, C3 and C4 plants are alike in the basic photosynthetic pathways such as Calvin-Benson cycle and electron transport chain components, significant differences exist in their response to environmental changes.",
